<a href="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/News/National_Article&sz=300x250&c=748595769&t=artid%3d88dacf36-34fa-4ebd-b97b-8222808b969a%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" target="_blank"><img src="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/News/National_Article&sz=300x250&c=748595769&t=artid%3d88dacf36-34fa-4ebd-b97b-8222808b969a%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" border="0" alt=""></a>More than 300 fishermen attended the fundraising event.Port manager Rajesh Dana said: “The People’s Port brought smiles to the faces of many less fortunate children in a unique way this festive season. “The fishing day is also another way to bring the city’s people into a port environment.“This is in line with our vision of creating a smart, people’s port. “We plan to host more events like open days, visits to navy vessels, fun runs and port festivals. “This will enable us to create a friendly environment for local and international tourists.”The kids live at the Inn Safe Hands in Schauderville, Aurora Special Care Centre in Walmer, Sinako-We Can in Newton Park and the Eastern Province Child and Youth Care Centre in Glendinningvale. “Our partnership with the community generated more than 230 toys which were handed over to four different charity organisations.“The key condition for participation in this fishing opportunity was the donation of toys valued at R100. “Their cash slips served as the admission fee in exchange for entrance tickets issued at the shops,” added Dana.“We got support from many stores including the Trophy Den, Hook, Line and Sinker, Commercial Marine and Extreme.”Terry Hattingh, director of the Child and Youth Care Centre, said it was an exciting day.She told Daily Sun: “We thank all those who truly made this day so special.” 
